  <div id="page-sources">
    <div class="hero" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
      <h1>Data <span>Sources</span><br>& Methodology</h1>
      <p>The technical dossier for the BoxFit engine: a from-scratch cargo fit system that turns messy vehicle specs, passenger layouts, rigid objects, powertrains, payload, and trip distance into a live 3D load plan.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="panel active">
      <h3 style="font-family:var(--display); font-size:1.5rem; letter-spacing:0.05em; margin-bottom:0.75rem; color:var(--orange);">The BoxFit Engine</h3>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--text); line-height:1.65; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        BoxFit was built from scratch as a deterministic cargo-planning engine, not a lookup table with a pretty car graphic on top. It models rigid household boxes, luggage, passenger seats, footwells, trunks, hatch areas, folded-seat decks, pickup beds, transmission tunnels, headrest limits, payload weight, highway MPG/MPGe, and loaded-vs-empty trip cost. It answers one practical question at serious depth: <b>given this exact loadout, this exact vehicle/year/powertrain, and this exact passenger count, what actually fits, where does it go, what shape of space remains, and what does that payload do to range and cost?</b>
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--text); line-height:1.65; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The breakthrough is that BoxFit does not stop at cargo cubic feet. Cubic feet alone cannot tell you whether a 22&quot; box clears a CX-90 tunnel, whether a folded deck can stack above a footwell layer, whether a rear passenger deletes half the usable cabin, or whether a BEV payload penalty should be treated like an ICE payload penalty. BoxFit turns those separate questions into one coordinated calculation. It is not an OEM CAD viewer, crash-safety model, or laser scan; it is a high-detail planning simulator that is honest about its approximations and ruthless about rejecting impossible geometry.
      </p>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">00 · Why This Changes the Cargo-Fit Game</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          Most cargo calculators compare <b>total cargo volume</b> against <b>item volume</b>. That sounds reasonable until reality shows up: an item can fail because it is too wide for a footwell, too tall for the headrest line, too deep for a trunk throat, blocked by a passenger, split by a transmission tunnel, or impossible to stack even while the dashboard still shows empty cubic feet. BoxFit treats fit as a geometry problem first and a volume problem second.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          The engine runs a full pipeline: normalize data, build a vehicle envelope, carve that envelope into live cargo zones, remove occupied passenger zones, apply tunnel and headrest constraints, test rigid objects in three dimensions, classify failures, estimate spare shape, render the result, and then run the payload/range/cost model. That is the difference between “your SUV has 37.6 cu ft” and “this exact set of boxes fits here, this one fails there, and the payload costs this much on a 500-mile trip.”
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">01 · Data Spine — The App Starts as a Database Problem</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          BoxFit begins by loading <b>db.js</b>, the data spine behind the whole simulator. It contains the item catalog, legacy vehicle coverage, MPG fallback tables, tank-size fallbacks, schema translators, US-market records, and VW/Mazda extensions. The UI does not hardcode a car menu. It asks the database what exists, then dynamically builds Make, Model, Year, and Powertrain controls from the live records.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          Every vehicle can carry model years, vehicle type, seat count, fold behavior, cargo volume, curb weight, rectangular cargo bounds, tunnel height, tunnel width, headrest height, headrest-to-seatback distance, drivetrain, engine label, MPG/MPGe, and powertrain category. Newer high-detail records overlay older broad-coverage records. Missing values go through a fallback ladder: exact record first, model average second, class fallback third. That is deliberate engineering hygiene, not hand-waving.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">02 · Loadout Catalog — Boxes Become Physical Objects</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          Every selectable object is treated as a physical cuboid with width, height, depth, volume, weight, cargo type, and seat-eligibility metadata. Moving boxes use Home Depot-style carton dimensions; luggage uses common personal-item, carry-on, and checked-bag dimensions. BoxFit computes item volume as <b>width × height × depth / 1,728</b>, because the packing engine works in inches while the dashboard reports cubic feet.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          Volume and weight are intentionally separate. A wardrobe box can be physically huge but relatively light; a medium box can be smaller and much heavier. Each item carries a planning weight, and the payload engine sums <b>quantity × item_weight</b> across the loadout unless the user overrides total weight. That same item list therefore drives two systems at once: the 3D geometry solver and the powertrain payload model.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">03 · Vehicle Envelope — Turning Public Specs Into a 3D Stage</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          Public vehicle specs are messy. Some records expose rectangular cargo bounds; others expose cargo volume, legroom, headroom, tunnel dimensions, and headrest measurements. The solver needs a 3D stage, so BoxFit translates volume-first records into <b>dimensions_inches</b>: cargo width, cargo height, trunk depth, and folded depth. The core translation is: <b>cargo_volume_in³ = trunk_space_cu_ft × 1,728</b>, then <b>depth_trunk = cargo_volume_in³ / (class_width × class_height)</b>.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          The translator does not pretend all cars are the same rectangle. A compact sedan, midsize sedan, hatchback, compact SUV, 3-row SUV, EV crossover, and full-size truck each get a different class envelope. Cargo volume controls depth; vehicle class controls width and height; folded-seat assumptions control extended deck depth; tunnel and headrest fields reshape the cabin. It is a disciplined approximation: strong enough for planning rigid cargo, honest enough to admit it is not OEM sheet-metal CAD.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">04 · Cabin Partitioning — The Vehicle Is Split Into Legal Cargo Zones</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          After the vehicle envelope is built, BoxFit carves it into legal cargo zones: trunk or pickup bed, folded-seat deck, below-deck footwell layers, rear left/right/middle seats, rear left/right/middle footwells, third-row footwells for 3-row vehicles, front passenger seat, front passenger footwell, and truck cab/bed regions where applicable. Passenger count is not cosmetic. It deletes occupied seats and their associated floor space from the solve. The driver is always counted, because the driver's position is never cargo.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          Folded-seat modeling is one of the places where BoxFit gets serious. If the rear bench can fold and passengers allow it, the folded deck becomes an upper cargo plane while the footwell beneath becomes a separate lower cargo layer. In 3-row vehicles, BoxFit adds an additional third-row footwell layer estimated from rear legroom and constrained by the same tunnel rules. The engine does not flatten that into one blob; it keeps the layers separate so stackability, under-deck fit, and row-specific footwell pockets are tested independently.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">05 · Tunnel Physics — Why the Middle Floor Is Not Free Real Estate</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          Transmission tunnels are where naive cargo math falls apart. BoxFit uses <b>transmission_tunnel_width_in</b> and <b>transmission_tunnel_height_in</b> as first-class geometry, not as trivia. A high tunnel splits the rear floor into left and right side lanes plus a raised center strip. The usable side-lane width is effectively <b>(cabin_width − tunnel_width) / 2</b>. If a box is wider than that lane, it cannot be placed there just because the total row width looks large.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          Flat-floor EVs and low-tunnel trucks are treated differently from RWD/AWD cabins with big center humps. If the tunnel is absent or low enough to bridge, BoxFit creates a full-width raised floor surface and tests wide boxes across it. If it is tall, the solver sees split lanes. That is the difference between a flat Model Y rear floor accepting a wide floor load and a CX-90 rejecting a 22&quot; XL box from an 18&quot; side footwell lane. This is the kind of detail ordinary cargo-volume specs completely miss.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">06 · Headrest and Seatback Geometry — The Clip Guard</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          Seat areas are not infinite vertical boxes. BoxFit uses the reported max headrest line as a ceiling and reserves <b>headrest_distance_from_seatback_in</b> as a buffer near the angled seatback. That buffer reduces usable deck depth and effective stack height so cargo does not visually or mathematically pass through the seatback/headrest region.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          The practical ceiling is built from three numbers: seat deck height establishes the floor, headrest height establishes the upper boundary, and the seatback buffer subtracts the risky zone near the seatback. A 12&quot; high box may fit on a rear seat where the buffered usable height is 13.5&quot;; a stack of three 12&quot; boxes will not, even if a cubic-foot-only calculator would say there is room. BoxFit rejects the stack because geometry beats volume.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">07 · Fit Engine — What It Reveals, What It Keeps Private</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          This is the heart of the machine. The fit engine tests rigid, axis-aligned objects against generated vehicle zones while width, height, depth, zone ceiling, tunnel limits, passenger occupancy, folded-seat state, footwell layers, and seat safety rules are all active at the same time. It distinguishes between <b>over capacity</b> and <b>spatial misfit</b>: over capacity means the requested cargo volume exceeds usable capacity; spatial misfit means volume remains, but the remaining shape cannot accept the object.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          The public explanation stops at the constraint model. The proprietary part is the exact placement heuristic: how candidate positions are ranked, how competing placements are scored, how ties are resolved, and how final layout priority is chosen. What the site does disclose is enough to audit the result without handing over the private engine: item dimensions, vehicle dimensions, occupied zones, failed items, total fitted count, used volume by zone, spare-room estimates, notes, and a 3D rendering of the chosen placement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">08 · Spare Room — The App Tests the Remaining Shape, Not Just Empty Volume</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          When everything fits, BoxFit does not celebrate with a lazy “space remaining” number and call it done. It estimates what else could still be added by running additional trial loadouts against the current solved vehicle, passenger layout, and cargo state. The Room to Spare chips are not simple cubic-foot division. They are shape-aware 3D tests against the remaining usable geometry.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          This is why the spare-room section can say "+20 Small Box" but not necessarily "+1 Wardrobe Box." Small boxes can exploit fragmented leftover pockets. Tall or wide boxes need continuous height, width, and depth. BoxFit treats those as different questions because in the real world they are different questions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">09 · 3D Visualizer — The Rendering Is a Readout of the Solve</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          The Three.js scene is the instrument panel for the solve. It draws zone outlines, folded-deck boundaries, truck cab/bed separation, cargo boxes, luggage boxes, and edge outlines. Orange objects are moving boxes; purple objects are luggage; dashed/outlined volumes are available cargo or seat/foot zones. The visualizer is not a decorative animation; it is a spatial readout of the engine's result.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          On each full redraw, BoxFit removes old scene objects and disposes their geometries and materials before rebuilding the next scene. That prevents repeated vehicle changes, passenger changes, and loadout changes from leaking stale WebGL resources. The trip slider does not redraw the scene because trip distance changes cost math, not cargo geometry.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">10 · Payload and Range — The Weight Engine</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          Payload begins as the sum of item weights, but the user can override it with a custom total. That final payload feeds the range engine. BoxFit selects base highway MPG or MPGe from the chosen powertrain when available, then falls back to model averages, legacy ranges, or class defaults if the exact trim is missing. It does not apply a separate drivetrain multiplier, because drivetrain effects should already be present in the MPG/MPGe record.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          The payload penalty is deliberately visible and easy to verify: <b>ICE = 1.5% MPG loss per 100 lb</b>, <b>HEV/PHEV = 1.2%</b>, and <b>BEV = 1.8% range loss per 100 lb</b>. Formula: <b>adjusted MPG/MPGe = base MPG/MPGe × (1 − coefficient × payload_lb / 100)</b>. A 500 lb payload therefore produces a 7.5% ICE penalty, 6.0% hybrid penalty, or 9.0% BEV penalty. The app shows the coefficient and the math note so the result is inspectable, not mystical.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">11 · Trip Cost — Empty vs. Loaded, Same Route</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          The cost model compares two versions of the same route: empty vehicle at base MPG/MPGe, and loaded vehicle at adjusted MPG/MPGe. Trip distance comes from the slider or number input. Gas price defaults to $3.50/gal. Empty gallons are <b>miles / base MPG</b>; loaded gallons-equivalent are <b>miles / adjusted MPG</b>; empty cost and loaded cost multiply those values by price. The penalty cell isolates the marginal cost attributable to cargo weight.
        </p>
        <p class="method-body">
          For EVs, MPGe is gasoline-equivalent. BoxFit can compare energy intensity in a common unit, but it does not know your utility rate, charger losses, battery temperature, charging curve, or local demand pricing. That is why EV cost is labeled as an approximation rather than a real charging bill.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-block">
        <div class="method-block-title">12 · Performance Model — Heavy Math Only Runs When Geometry Changes</div>
        <p class="method-body">
          The engine is split into hot and cold paths. Vehicle changes, passenger changes, and loadout changes trigger the full simulation: database lookup, schema translation, zone generation, fit solve, spare-room trials, dashboard rebuild, notes, and 3D redraw. Trip distance, payload override, and powertrain selection use a fast payload-refresh path that updates only the range and cost blocks. That is why the fuel slider can feel instant without deleting any feature or dumbing down the math.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="method-foot">
        Limits, stated plainly: BoxFit models rigid rectangular cargo. It does not model soft-bag compression, diagonal loading, hatch curvature, wheel-well bulges, seat cushion deformation, cargo nets, tie-down safety, child seats, crash dynamics, or driver visibility law in every jurisdiction. Schema-translated vehicles are class-bounded estimates, not OEM CAD. Range and cost are planning estimates; real results vary with speed, road grade, temperature, wind, tires, HVAC, traffic, battery state, fuel grade, and driving style.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="panel active" style="padding:0; overflow:hidden;">
      <div class="table-wrap" style="margin-bottom: 0;">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>System Layer</th>
              <th>What Feeds It / What It Computes</th>
